# Create an mdoc credential

GOV.UK Wallet supports the mdoc (mobile document) credential format, defined by
[ISO/IEC 18013-5:2021](https://www.iso.org/standard/69084.html). If your department
has agreed with the GOV.UK Wallet onboarding team that you will issue an mdoc-based
credential â€” such as the mobile driving licence (mDL) â€” you must follow this guidance
when constructing and signing the credential.

This page covers the mdoc format only. If you are issuing a JWT-based verifiable
credential, see [Issue a credential](/issue-a-credential/credential/).

## What is an mdoc?

An mdoc stores each data element separately, so the holder can choose which individual
pieces of information to share with a verifier. This is called **selective disclosure**.
It is different from a JWT verifiable credential, where all claims are disclosed together
whenever the credential is presented.

**The envelope analogy.** Think of it like a tamper-evident envelope system. Your
department puts each piece of information â€” for example, someone's name or date of
birth â€” into a separate sealed envelope. You then photograph each sealed envelope
(that is the hash), and sign a document listing all the photographs (that is the
Mobile Security Object, or MSO). At verification time, the holder hands over only
the envelopes they choose to open. The verifier checks that each opened envelope's
contents match the photograph in the signed document, without ever needing to see
the other envelopes.

mdocs encode data using **CBOR (Concise Binary Object Representation)** â€” a compact
binary data format defined in RFC 7049, similar to JSON but more efficient and with
a type-tagging system. You do not need to understand the full CBOR specification to
implement this, but you do need a CBOR library. Most languages have one available.

## Before you start

Make sure the following are in place before you begin implementation:

- **Agreed docType and namespace strings** from the GOV.UK Wallet onboarding team. Do
  not use values you have invented yourself â€” unregistered docTypes will be rejected.
- **An IACA (Issuing Authority Certificate Authority) root certificate** and a
  **Document Signer certificate** issued under it, with the `id-mdoc-signer`
  Extended Key Usage (EKU) extension. See [Certificate requirements](#certificate-requirements)
  and [Manage keys](/manage-keys/).
- **Your IACA root registered with GOV.UK Wallet.** This must be done before
  end-to-end testing is possible. Contact the GOV.UK Wallet onboarding team to
  arrange this early.
- **A CBOR library** for your implementation language.
- **The wallet's device public key** (`did:key`) â€” GOV.UK Wallet includes this in
  the proof of possession when it calls your `/credential` endpoint.

## Understand the mdoc issuance flow

The credential exchange flow for mdoc credentials follows the same
[OID4VCI flow](/issuing-credentials-to-wallet.html) as JWT-based credentials, with
one key difference: when your service builds the credential in step 13, you must
construct an mdoc rather than a JWT VC.

